{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "In unpaired settings, the KID [2] uses features extracted from an Inception network and measures the distance between their distributions with kernel methods.",
    "The KID score is averaged over multiple kernels and sample sizes using the formula:KID ¼ 1 M X M i¼1 E x;x 0 kðx; x 0 Þ ½ ÀE x;x 00 kðx; x 00 Þ ½ Â Ãwhere k is the kernel function, and x, x 0, and x 00 are samples from the distributions.",
    "Lower KID values indicate better alignment with real image distributions.",
    "Together, these metrics provide a thorough assessment of image coherence and realism.",
    "For the LPIPS and SSIM implementation, the torch-metrics Python package [7] was used, while for the FID and KID scores, the implementation in [25] was employed.The Viton-HD dataset [5] comprises 13,679 image pairs, each composed of a frontal view of a woman and an upperbody clothing item with a resolution equal to 10249768."
  ],
